(452, 1, '2017-12-31 21:15:57', '2017-12-31 21:15:57', '<p style=\"text-align: center;\">Once the children complete doing their test of attention the teacher can scan the list of children from within the system and assess their individual level of attentional capabilities. At this stage, if attentional difficulties are spotted, it will be suggested to refer the child to further diagnosis</p>		\n			<figure><img src=\"https://axon.digitalim.co.il/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/kid_1.png\" alt=\"kid_1\" title=\"kid_1\"></figure><h3>Emily, 7 years old</h3><p>Emily, seven years old isn’t coping with her homework; it is very hard for her. She is never at ease; she becomes impatient, acts impulsively and tends to fight with her siblings which causes tension and makes it difficult to have a quiet evening at home.  </p>		\n			<figure><img src=\"https://axon.digitalim.co.il/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/kid_2.png\" alt=\"kid_2\" title=\"kid_2\"></figure><h3>Roy, 6 years old</h3><p>Roy, six years old, started first grade this year. While still in kindergarten his teacher advised his parents that he is unable to sit still; he is always running around and endangering himself.\n<br>\n</p>		\n			<figure><img src=\"https://axon.digitalim.co.il/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/kid_3.png\" alt=\"kid_3\" title=\"kid_3\"></figure><h3>Andy, 8.5 years old</h3><p>Andy, eight-and-a-half years old, is a quiet child who and according to his parents, has difficulty completing tasks. Every little noise or movement can easily distract him and it is a challenge for him to return to the task at hand.</p>		\n		<p style=\"text-align: center;\">What is common in all these cases is the fact that these kids are dealing with difficulties maintaining their focus, behavior and attention, and might have ADHD (Attention Deficit Hyperactivity Disorder).</p><p><strong>The system will automatically produce three reports for each child, these reports are associated with the child\'s Individual attention profile.</strong></p>		\n			<figure><a href=\"https://axon.digitalim.co.il/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/Axon-School_Techers-report_example.pdf\" target=\"_blank\"><img src=\"https://axon.digitalim.co.il/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/icon_3.png\" alt=\"icon_3\" title=\"icon_3\"></a></figure><h3><a href=\"https://axon.digitalim.co.il/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/Axon-School_Techers-report_example.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">A teacher report</a></h3><p>With comparative results and suggested techniques that the teacher can implement in class for the specific child and that can assist his learning.\n<a href=\"https://axon.digitalim.co.il/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/Axon-School_Techers-report_example.pdf\"target=\"_blank\">Click for an example >></a></p>		\n			<figure><a href=\"https://axon.digitalim.co.il/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/409_parents_report-2.pdf\" target=\"_blank\"><img src=\"https://axon.digitalim.co.il/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/icon_4.png\" alt=\"icon_4\" title=\"icon_4\"></a></figure><h3><a href=\"https://axon.digitalim.co.il/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/409_parents_report-2.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">A Parent report</a></h3><p>suggesting techniques parents can use at home to strengthen their child social and learning abilities.<br><a href=\"https://axon.digitalim.co.il/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/409_parents_report-2.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Click for an example &gt;&gt;</a></p>		\n			<figure><a href=\"https://axon.digitalim.co.il/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/Axon-School_ParentStudent-report_example.pdf\" target=\"_blank\"><img src=\"https://axon.digitalim.co.il/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/icon_5.png\" alt=\"icon_5\" title=\"icon_5\"></a></figure><h3><a href=\"https://axon.digitalim.co.il/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/Axon-School_ParentStudent-report_example.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">A child report</a></h3><p>The third report goes to the child himself. This time, showing the child his strengths and weaknesses in regards to his attention, suggesting technics that could make a difference in his life. <br><a href=\"https://axon.digitalim.co.il/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/Axon-School_ParentStudent-report_example.pdf\"target=\"_blank\">Click for an example >></a></p>		\n		<p>School Counselors have additional benefits from the system allowing them an aggregated view of the entire class and grade. For more information go to <em><u>School strategies</u></em>.</p>		\n		<img width=\"1024\" height=\"682\" src=\"https://axon.digitalim.co.il/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/girl-in-classroom-1024x682.jpg\" alt=\"\" srcset=\"https://axon.digitalim.co.il/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/girl-in-classroom-1024x682.jpg 1024w, https://axon.digitalim.co.il/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/girl-in-classroom-300x200.jpg 300w, https://axon.digitalim.co.il/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/girl-in-classroom-768x512.jpg 768w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px\" />		\n		<h3>School Strategies</h3><p>AXON-School™ integrates a comprehensive view of the entire classroom and of the entire grade. These can be especially useful for class behavioral and performance management by the teacher and for the same management on a grade level usually done by a school counselor. <br />Try to recall a class you have been teaching that were notorious around school for being very difficult and noisy, this could be a very frustrating class, and many teachers feel that they do not possess the right tools to deal with such a class. We know that the attentional profile of a class could be an important starting point for a change. Imagine that based on the test results you find out that around 40% of your students are Impulsive-Hyperactive, and that many of them are highly distracted by visual stimulation. This knowledge can dramatically change the way you perceive your class, and we even make suggestions on what could work better in such a case.</p><p><a href=\"https://axon.digitalim.co.il/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/Axon-School-counselor-report.pdf\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"> Click here for an example of such a report.</a></p>', 'AXON-School™ system', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '193-revision-v1', '', '', '2017-12-31 21:15:57', '2017-12-31 21:15:57', '', 193, 'https://axon.digitalim.co.il/2017/12/31/193-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(453, 1, '2017-12-31 21:18:37', '2017-12-31 21:18:37', '<p style=\"text-align: center;\">Once the children complete doing their test of attention the teacher can scan the list of children from within the system and assess their individual level of attentional capabilities. At this stage, if attentional difficulties are spotted, it will be suggested to refer the child to further diagnosis</p>		\n			<figure><img src=\"https://axon.digitalim.co.il/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/kid_1.png\" alt=\"kid_1\" title=\"kid_1\"></figure><h3>Emily, 7 years old</h3><p>Emily, seven years old isn’t coping with her homework; it is very hard for her. She is never at ease; she becomes impatient, acts impulsively and tends to fight with her siblings which causes tension and makes it difficult to have a quiet evening at home.  </p>		\n			<figure><img src=\"https://axon.digitalim.co.il/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/kid_2.png\" alt=\"kid_2\" title=\"kid_2\"></figure><h3>Roy, 6 years old</h3><p>Roy, six years old, started first grade this year. While still in kindergarten his teacher advised his parents that he is unable to sit still; he is always running around and endangering himself.\n<br>\n</p>		\n			<figure><img src=\"https://axon.digitalim.co.il/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/kid_3.png\" alt=\"kid_3\" title=\"kid_3\"></figure><h3>Andy, 8.5 years old</h3><p>Andy, eight-and-a-half years old, is a quiet child who and according to his parents, has difficulty completing tasks. Every little noise or movement can easily distract him and it is a challenge for him to return to the task at hand.</p>		\n		<p style=\"text-align: center;\">What is common in all these cases is the fact that these kids are dealing with difficulties maintaining their focus, behavior and attention, and might have ADHD (Attention Deficit Hyperactivity Disorder).</p><p><strong>The system will automatically produce three reports for each child, these reports are associated with the child\'s Individual attention profile.</strong></p>		\n			<figure><a href=\"https://axon.digitalim.co.il/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/Axon-School_Techers-report_example.pdf\" target=\"_blank\"><img src=\"https://axon.digitalim.co.il/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/icon_3.png\" alt=\"icon_3\" title=\"icon_3\"></a></figure><h3><a href=\"https://axon.digitalim.co.il/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/Axon-School_Techers-report_example.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">A teacher report</a></h3><p>With comparative results and suggested techniques that the teacher can implement in class for the specific child and that can assist his learning.\n<a href=\"https://axon.digitalim.co.il/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/Axon-School_Techers-report_example.pdf\"target=\"_blank\">Click for an example >></a></p>		\n			<figure><a href=\"https://axon.digitalim.co.il/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/409_parents_report-2.pdf\" target=\"_blank\"><img src=\"https://axon.digitalim.co.il/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/icon_4.png\" alt=\"icon_4\" title=\"icon_4\"></a></figure><h3><a href=\"https://axon.digitalim.co.il/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/409_parents_report-2.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">A Parent report</a></h3><p>suggesting techniques parents can use at home to strengthen their child social and learning abilities.<br><a href=\"https://axon.digitalim.co.il/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/409_parents_report-2.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Click for an example &gt;&gt;</a></p>		\n			<figure><a href=\"https://axon.digitalim.co.il/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/Axon-School_ParentStudent-report_example.pdf\" target=\"_blank\"><img src=\"https://axon.digitalim.co.il/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/icon_5.png\" alt=\"icon_5\" title=\"icon_5\"></a></figure><h3><a href=\"https://axon.digitalim.co.il/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/Axon-School_ParentStudent-report_example.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">A child report</a></h3><p>The third report goes to the child himself. This time, showing the child his strengths and weaknesses in regards to his attention, suggesting technics that could make a difference in his life. <br><a href=\"https://axon.digitalim.co.il/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/Axon-School_ParentStudent-report_example.pdf\"target=\"_blank\">Click for an example >></a></p>		\n		<p>School Counselors have additional benefits from the system allowing them an aggregated view of the entire class and grade. For more information go to <a href=\"#School strategies.\"><em><u>School strategies</u></em>.</a></p>		\n		<img width=\"1024\" height=\"682\" src=\"https://axon.digitalim.co.il/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/girl-in-classroom-1024x682.jpg\" alt=\"\" srcset=\"https://axon.digitalim.co.il/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/girl-in-classroom-1024x682.jpg 1024w, https://axon.digitalim.co.il/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/girl-in-classroom-300x200.jpg 300w, https://axon.digitalim.co.il/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/girl-in-classroom-768x512.jpg 768w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px\" />		\n		<h3>School Strategies</h3><p>AXON-School™ integrates a comprehensive view of the entire classroom and of the entire grade. These can be especially useful for class behavioral and performance management by the teacher and for the same management on a grade level usually done by a school counselor. <br />Try to recall a class you have been teaching that were notorious around school for being very difficult and noisy, this could be a very frustrating class, and many teachers feel that they do not possess the right tools to deal with such a class. We know that the attentional profile of a class could be an important starting point for a change. Imagine that based on the test results you find out that around 40% of your students are Impulsive-Hyperactive, and that many of them are highly distracted by visual stimulation. This knowledge can dramatically change the way you perceive your class, and we even make suggestions on what could work better in such a case.</p><p><a href=\"https://axon.digitalim.co.il/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/Axon-School-counselor-report.pdf\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"> Click here for an example of such a report.</a></p>', 'AXON-School™ system', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '193-revision-v1', '', '', '2017-12-31 21:18:37', '2017-12-31 21:18:37', '', 193, 'https://axon.digitalim.co.il/2017/12/31/193-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(454, 1, '2017-12-31 21:26:57', '2017-12-31 21:26:57', '<p>Through hours of research, focus group meetings and expert\'s contribution we created a collection of comprehensive behavioral, academic and cognitive recommendations that are geared to help children overcome attention shortcomings and at times also teach them how to utilize their unique attentive profile to their advantage. These recommendations are featured in the teacher, parent and student reports.</p><p>Each child performing the test will receive recommendations, even if the performance on the test was flawless. The right way to use these recommendations is to choose from the list just two to three recommendations at a time and try them out for fit, before moving to the next set of recommendations.</p><p>We are always happy to hear your feedback and ideas on additional recommendations that work from your experience. Just get in touch with us <a href=\"https://axon.digitalim.co.il/general/contact-as/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><em><u>here</u></em> </a>and let us know.</p>		\n		', 'The recommendations', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '225-revision-v1', '', '', '2017-12-31 21:26:57', '2017-12-31 21:26:57', '', 225, 'https://axon.digitalim.co.il/2017/12/31/225-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(455, 1, '2017-12-31 21:28:30', '2017-12-31 21:28:30', '<p><strong>The</strong><b> AXON-School™</b> test measures Attention based indices that have been validated through a clinical trial and standardized to be used in a school setting. Attentiveness, Impulsivity and hyper-reactivity are indices that compare the examinee to other subjects of the same age and gender. The other indices that we present compare the examinee to his baseline performance. </p><h5> </h5>		\n		<img width=\"1024\" height=\"302\" src=\"https://axon.digitalim.co.il/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/img-1024x302.png\" alt=\"\" srcset=\"https://axon.digitalim.co.il/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/img-1024x302.png 1024w, https://axon.digitalim.co.il/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/img-300x88.png 300w, https://axon.digitalim.co.il/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/img-768x227.png 768w, https://axon.digitalim.co.il/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/img.png 1146w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px\" />		\n			<h2>COMPARATIVE MEASURES > ></h2>		\n								<img width=\"100\" height=\"100\" src=\"https://axon.digitalim.co.il/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/icon_11.png\" alt=\"\" />							\n													<h3>\n								ATTENTIVENESS							</h3>\n								The ability of the child to correctly evaluate and respond to a stimulus							\n													<h3>\n								 Level of attention							</h3>\n								(Attentive vs. Inattentive) ability of the student to respond correctly to the target element and remain focused throughout the test. (measure of sustained attention).							\n								<img width=\"100\" height=\"100\" src=\"https://axon.digitalim.co.il/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/icon_22.png\" alt=\"\" />							\n													<h3>\n								Impulsiveness							</h3>\n								The tendency of the child to react the wrong target\n													<h3>\n								Level of Impulsiveness							</h3>\n								(Self-controlled vs. Impulsive) – Measurement of responses to non-targets during the test.							\n								<img width=\"100\" height=\"100\" src=\"https://axon.digitalim.co.il/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/icon_33.png\" alt=\"\" />							\n													<h3>\n								Responsiveness 							</h3>\n								Excessive responses to the target element\n													<h3>\n								Level of responsiveness 							</h3>\n								(Responsiveness regulated vs. over responsive) – Measurement of the number of responses the student is making for each target.The thre indices above have been tested in a clinical trial of over 798 children, and were found to have an excellent sensitivity profile of 90% and Specificity of 86%. \n			<h2>Non-Comparative indices:</h2>		\n		<p>The AXON-School™ test makes use of several non-comparative indices related to the performance of the examinee throughout the test in relation to his base performance. This allows us to examine the impact of distractors and time on the student overall performance.</p>		\n                <h3>\n                    Visual Distractibility\n                </h3>\n                <p> a measure of the effect of visual distractions on performance.</p>\n                <h3>\n                    Auditory Distractibility\n                </h3>\n                <p>a measure of the effect of auditory distractions on performance.</p>\n                <h3>\n                    Distraction load\n                </h3>\n                <p>a measure of the effect of distraction load on performance.</p>\n                <h3>\n                    Sustained attention\n                </h3>\n                <p>the effect of time on performance.\n</p>\n		', 'What do we actually measure ?', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '213-revision-v1', '', '', '2017-12-31 21:28:30', '2017-12-31 21:28:30', '', 213, 'https://axon.digitalim.co.il/2017/12/31/213-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
